outputSummary:
Generics in TypeScript allow you to write **reusable code components** that work with multiple types rather than a single one. They provide type safety while maintaining flexibility.

## Simple Example: Identity Function

```typescript
// Without generics - you'd need separate functions
function returnString(arg: string): string {
  return arg;
}

function returnNumber(arg: number): number {
  return arg;
}

// With generics - one function works for all types
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
  return arg;
}

// TypeScript infers the type automatically
const message = identity("hello");        // Type: string
const count = identity(42);               // Type: number
const flag = identity(true);              // Type: boolean

// You can also specify the type explicitly
const num = identity<number>("123");      // Error! "123" is not a number
```

## Key Concepts

1. **`<T>`** - Type parameter (like a variable for types)
2. **`T`** in parameters/return type - "use whatever type was provided"
3. **Type inference** - TypeScript often figures out `T` automatically
4. **Constraints** - You can limit what types are allowed

## Practical Example: Array Wrapper

```typescript
class Box<T> {
  private items: T[] = [];

  add(item: T): void {
    this.items.push(item);
  }

  get(index: number): T | undefined {
    return this.items[index];
  }

  // Generic method within a generic class
  find<U extends T>(predicate: (item: T) => item is U): U | undefined {
    return this.items.find(predicate);
  }
}

// Usage
const stringBox = new Box<string>();
stringBox.add("apple");
stringBox.add(123);  // Error!

const numberBox = new Box<number>();
numberBox.add(42);
```

## Built-in Generic Examples

TypeScript uses generics everywhere in the standard library:

```typescript
const numbers: Array<number> = [1, 2, 3];
const map: Map<string, number> = new Map();

// Promise is generic - Promise<T> resolves to type T
const dataPromise: Promise<string> = fetch("/api").then(r => r.text());
```

Generics give you **flexibility** (work with any type) + **safety** (TypeScript knows exactly which type you're using).

# TypeScript Error Handling Best Practices

Based on your project's coding standards, here are the key TypeScript error handling practices:

## 1. Comprehensive Error Handling (MANDATORY)

Always handle errors explicitly at every level:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Comprehensive error handling
async function fetchData(url: string): Promise<Data> {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url)

    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`)
    }

    return await response.json()
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Fetch failed:', error)
    throw new Error('Failed to fetch data')
  }
}

// ❌ BAD: No error handling
async function fetchData(url) {
  const response = await fetch(url)
  return response.json()
}
```

## 2. Custom Error Types

Create typed error classes for better error discrimination:

```typescript
// Define custom error types
class NetworkError extends Error {
  constructor(message: string, public statusCode: number) {
    super(message)
    this.name = 'NetworkError'
  }
}

class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(message: string, public field: string) {
    super(message)
    this.name = 'ValidationError'
  }
}

// Usage with type narrowing
try {
  await apiCall()
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof NetworkError) {
    // Handle network errors
  } else if (error instanceof ValidationError) {
    // Handle validation errors
  } else {
    // Handle unknown errors
  }
}
```

## 3. Input Validation with Zod

Validate at system boundaries before processing:

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod'

const CreateMarketSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1).max(200),
  description: z.string().min(1).max(2000),
  endDate: z.string().datetime(),
  categories: z.array(z.string()).min(1)
})

export async function POST(request: Request) {
  const body = await request.json()

  try {
    const validated = CreateMarketSchema.parse(body)
    // Proceed with validated data
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof z.ZodError) {
      return NextResponse.json({
        success: false,
        error: 'Validation failed',
        details: error.errors
      }, { status: 400 })
    }
  }
}
```

## 4. Consistent API Response Format

Use a consistent envelope for all API responses:

```typescript
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  success: boolean
  data?: T
  error?: string
  meta?: {
    total: number
    page: number
    limit: number
  }
}

// Success response
return NextResponse.json({
  success: true,
  data: markets,
  meta: { total: 100, page: 1, limit: 10 }
})

// Error response
return NextResponse.json({
  success: false,
  error: 'Invalid request'
}, { status: 400 })
```

## 5. Error Handling Best Practices Summary

| Practice | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| **Explicit handling** | Handle errors at every level, never silently swallow |
| **User-friendly messages** | Clear error messages in UI-facing code |
| **Detailed logging** | Log detailed error context on server side |
| **Type safety** | Use typed errors and instanceof checks |
| **Validation at boundaries** | Validate input before processing |
| **Consistent format** | Use standard response envelopes |
| **No secrets in errors** | Never expose sensitive data in error messages |

